arolinas in Eastern Carolina, particularly in more rural areas. I've also heard it from both southern black and white speakers in the region and had assumed it was a property of Southern dialect. It isn't used for all cases and most often you will see or hear it used in the case of multiple verbs,'A-jumpin' and A-hoppin'' or 'A-huntin' and A-fishin'' being the most common pairs I've heard. Typically it is used when the verbs in question are thought to be related in some sense, or commonly done together. This appears to be different than the example provided in the Yale Grammatical Diversity Project which display more uses of single verbs with A-prefixing, and this could be a property of A-prefixing that is more distinct for Appalachia and the Ozarks. %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
